metadata.name: Celestial Objects #24
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #237
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: Origami. #15
metadata.description:
This piece, as suggested by the name, stems from an old art form that came from Japan about 1000 years ago. And has been practiced by people all around the world ever since.

My goal with this piece was to capture the feeling of origami and everything that comes with it, the paper texture, the delicate and often complicated folds, the colors, everything.

- Press [I] for information about your token (rarities, descriptions, etc.)
- Press [E] to open up the export settings, here you can export your token in up to 5000x5000 resolution.
- Press [<-] to show step counters, showing the process of the folds.

--------------------------------------------------

As for features, we have a couple:

Grid size: ranging from 1x1 all the way to 3x4
Color scheme: a total of 7 (possibly 9) color schemes are available.
Background: either dark or light.
Background feature: if your grid is 1x1 you can have background features.
Outlines: if you have outlines, your Origami will be transformed into Kirigami. (this is toggle-able)

metadata.name: PolyGarden #228
metadata.description:
Polygons, patterns and flowers are mixtured in my garden. I start with a birdeye view of the garden and its geometric structure. The species diversity and the random stack of rocks, sands, fences and other objects are main structures I want to capture, in an abstract and planar style. 

Moreover, in this project, I also try to explore the representation ability of generative art. I select three elements: shape of entity, layout of palette, and stack of object location. The factors behind these elements are the balance of randomness and structure: the generative art generates the variants from randomness but restricts its chaos with structure (deterministic constraints) to represent the meaningful results. 

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 6 texture patterns
- 15 color palette
- 3 randomness
- 2 completeness

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #64
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.

metadata.name: Attractor #103
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‘p’ to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Foundations #250
metadata.description:
In march of this year, I started working on a new series involving multi-layering, and overriding shapes. Drawing and playing with colors and opacity.
It started with squares and grid, it then involved deformations, and circles and other experimentations.
This path fits with my artistic generative approach: rather than having a completely predefined idea, I start with a simple concept that evolves during creation. Then surprises happened, and I embraced them.

But this year was not like any other: 2022 has gifted me with a new birthday, the one of my son.

Over the past twelve months, I’ve watched him discovering the world surrounding him, learning and trying new things, laughing, or getting frustrated, sad or happy…
While learning to become a parent, I’ve been in an introspection phase where I questioned what it means to be “a father”. What impact will I have on my son, consciously or not?

“Foundations” takes shape in this context: 2 humans trying and exploring while being inspired by each other.
This series is a first of a set of at least 3, that illustrates an idea of what is an “Identity”, and what makes us who we are.

The foundations of an identity are laid in the first days of a child’s life. They will be influenced by many factors; including parenting, cultural environment, life experiences… 
Of course, as humans we are in constant evolution; life happens, sometimes for the best, sometimes for the worst, and our personality will be impacted…
But this will be a topic for another time. 


Today, we are at the start.

metadata.name: Moonlit Native Bush #54
metadata.description:
Moonlit Native Bush with Fog is a dense forest scene that uses shaders to achieve effects that would be difficult or impossible in plain p5js.

The moon, corona, grain, and fog are rendered in a shader. The shader slows the rendering a little, but considering the effects it can achieve, it's not much.

The moon color is one of the palette colors with the luminance toned down to a reasonable level. The fog color is the moon color mixed with some white to shade it just a touch. 

Moonlit Native Bush is responsive and looks great on any size display up to 4K, but may take some time to render on very large screens.

Since Moonlit Native Bush uses shaders, a decent gpu is recommended.

Variations:

- 41 palettes and small drop means a big chance of getting a unique palette.
- All layouts unique
- Fog Intensity
- Fog Speed X
- Fog SpeedY
- Moon Size
- Moon Blur
- Graininess

'f' toggles the fog.
'a' toggles the animation.

metadata.name: Ars Mystica #8
metadata.description:
As the artist sat at her computer, she couldn't help but feel a sense of excitement and anticipation. She had spent months refining her generative art piece, a jungle of shapes that seemed to pulse and swirl with life. Using the rough.js library, she had crafted each and every one of the shapes with precise control, carefully balancing order and chaos to create a mesmerizing and dynamic piece of art.

Finally, she was ready to unveil her creation to the world. She hit the "publish" button, and the art piece went live on fxhash. Within minutes, the responses started pouring in. People from all over the world were marveling at the jungle of shapes, each one a unique and intricate creation.

As the artist sat back and watched the reactions roll in, she couldn't help but feel a sense of pride and accomplishment. She had poured her heart and soul into this piece, and it seemed to be resonating with people in a way she could have never imagined. And as she gazed at the jungle of shapes on her screen, she knew that this was only the beginning. There were so many more art pieces waiting to be created, and she couldn't wait to see where her imagination would take her next.

In live mode Press "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
Ars Mystica by __Reiji_c
+---+
Made with vanilla javascript + (roughjs MIT License (c) Preet Shihn)

metadata.name: Circumscript #134
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.
